text: I may have to use Python for my job everyday now but I miss R. It is just so easy and elegant! Btw dplyr > pandas #rstats #python
@coolbutuseless Quality documentation, including vignettes and a nice open repository on GitHub, is big factor determining whether I use an #RStats package.

@Shel_Kariuki I was reading this very article this morning,  and for someone who was trained to use Perl, taught myself Python and R, I must say these arguments are outright comical. #RStats community active; R is robust  and has a reliable IDE in RStudio. Introduction of Quarto is also timely

While looking into older GUI packages on CRAN, I have "discovered" that the level of instructive documentation for many packages is frickin' woeful!

#RStats https://t.co/1Lvg9xoex9
#RStats {tcltk} modern usage in the wild!!! https://t.co/Se99qfiHMo

This was called {gridui}, and it helped me work out some concepts, but I think it might be a dead-end.

There were too many ideas that I couldn't figure out within this framework e.g. the concept of separate windows, dragging windows, pop-ups.

#RStats #GUI

#RStats hivemind: Does anyone write non-shiny GUIs for their #RStats work?

Does anyone *want* to write non-shiny GUIs for R?

What's your use case?  

What tools do you currently use?
Followup question: if you could easily write a gui in #RStats, what would you do with it?

I'm wondering what might have been if {tcltk} was promoted/nutured/documented as a first-class interactivity solution.

Has anyone actually *tried* {tcltk} ?  Seems like 'abandonware' even though it's builtin to every R installation!

#RStats

Experiment with GUIs in #RStats earlier in the year showed some things possible with abstraction layer on top of grid.

Here's a calendar created in this system, and the code used to create it.

Each date is "clickable" within an {eventloop} context. https://t.co/LdARe3c1Tt

And this video is the "pinnacle" of this experiment.

A {gridui} UI running in #RStats returning the date corresponding to the user's mouse click.

This includes "month" navigation as well!

#RStats #GUI https://t.co/kjLvWEZrxC

@nischaldesign The timing is driven by the {eventloop} package.

In summary the "play note" function is called continuously, but in between another function checks the time, and inserts pauses to ensure the function is called at a constant tempo.

See eventloop/src/utils-governor.c
#RStats

The bespoke GUI for this TR-808 drum machine in #RStats was a bit of a pain to create

E.g. for every mouse click, a manual calc is done to see which button is closest

Worked out to be not too much work for this use-case, but I'm definitely thinking of better options https://t.co/FCjwU0LM3E

1/ bootstrap with tidymodels #rstats 
library(tidymodels)
Auto_boots <- bootstraps(mtcars, times = 100)

boot.fn <- function(split) {
  lm_fit <- lm_spec %>% fit(mpg ~ hp + gear , data = analysis(split))
  tidy(lm_fit)
}

2/ 
boot_res <- Auto_boots %>%
  mutate(models = map(splits, boot.fn))

boot_res %>%
  unnest(cols = c(models)) %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(estimate),
            sd = sd(estimate))

2. Speaking of eye movement, limit it. Don't make your audience's eyes travel from top right to the bottom left and then to the top left, all for one chart.

#Rstats #dataviz #datascience

3. Knock off axis labels and titles if they're obvious, if you've already mentioned it somewhere in the title or if you're labelling points in your charts. Reduce clutter and repetition.

#RStats #dataviz #datascience #datafam

1. Position the charts in the direction of eye movement in your #dataviz - from top to bottom and left to right. This is key to how you sequence your graphs and to drive your narrative 

#Rstats #dataviz #datafam #datascience

4. Check your data once, twice, thrice...ten times if you have to. Publishing a #dataviz with inaccurate data is as good as publishing nothing. Inaccurate data could mislead your audience.

Accuracy trumps speed and almost everything else.

#RStats #DataScience #Dataviz #Datafam

5. Credit your sources in your #dataviz. This will make your charts all the more accessible and credible, and will give your audience the chance to go back to the source, understand and explore the data a bit more if they want to.

#RStats #datafam #dataviz

The back and forth eye movement will a) make it longer for your audience to understand your chart and b) it'll put people away from engaging with your charts. 
Your #dataviz is not a puzzle you want your audience to solve, so make it as effortless as possible for them

#Rstats
